thrombin","Thrombin activates factor VII","Factor XII binds to collagen","Tissue factor binds to factor VII"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe extrinsic coagulation pathway begins when \u003Cstrong\u003Etissue factor binds to factor VII\u003C/strong\u003E. This complex then activates factor X, leading to the conversion of prothrombin to thrombin and ultimately fibrin formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor IX activates factor X\u003C/strong\u003E - This is part of the intrinsic pathway, not the initial step of the extrinsic pathway\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombin activates factor VII\u003C/strong\u003E - Thrombin is produced later in the cascade and does not activate factor VII\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor XII binds to collagen\u003C/strong\u003E - This interaction initiates the intrinsic pathway, not the extrinsic pathway\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium binds to prothrombin\u003C/strong\u003E - While calcium is important for coagulation, this is not the initiating step of the extrinsic pathway\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe tissue factor/factor VII complex provides rapid initiation of coagulation in response to tissue injury, making the extrinsic pathway particularly important for immediate haemostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The extrinsic coagulation pathway is initiated when tissue factor binds to factor VII, forming an active complex.","The extrinsic pathway activates factor X, which then converts prothrombin to thrombin.","The extrinsic pathway provides rapid initial activation of coagulation in response to tissue injury."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61381"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16854"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61381"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T05:28:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T05:28:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9544"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75868"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1003"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Clotting factors","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position"